            "text": "Who doesn't like pastries??? And savory pastries, much less. An 'Oggie', is the classic pasty that is still savored in Cornwall and all over the UK today. After hearing so many locals rave about the famous pastry, I had to pay the Cornish Pastry Company a visit. Talk about a British pub. This place mimics the dark, mysterious alley pubs in England. The restaurant is dim, moody and spacious with pool tables, a huge bar area and a misted patio. The vibe was very mellow on a weekday afternoon, but I can imagine it gets fairly busy on the weekends. After studying the extensive list of pastries (over two dozen), I went with the Carne Adovada from the premium list and the Cajun Chicken from the signature list and a side of the the broccoli cauliflower bake.\n\nThe broccoli cauliflower bake was delivered first. Think: healthy take on mac and cheese without giving up any of the flavor. The broccoli cauliflower dish was swimming in this wonderful cheese sauce and baked with tons of cheese on top creating a perfectly crisp exterior. Definitely delicious and a must order. \n\nThe pastries came next. Similar to a calzone but a lot less doughy, and a lot more flakey; the dough recipe is perfect because it is not overpowering to the savory delicious fillings. The Adovada was filled with simmered pork in New Mexican red chili stew, Mexican rice, hatch chilies and cheddar with a side of sour cream and salsa (the sides are switched in the photos). The pork was so tender and flavorful and the stew and chilies added a perfect kick. This was a British take on a Mexican influenced dish and it was a winner. The Cajun Chicken was filled with spicy cajun chicken breast, bacon, ham and Swiss and served with a side of chipotle sauce. The chicken was tender and the bacon added the right amount of smokiness paired with the chipotle sauce. I enjoyed this pastry as well, but the Adovada was the winner.\n\nWith so many options to choose from, you really can't go wrong here. I spend about fifteen minutes on the menu trying to decide which pasty to choose. There is something for everyone here with flavors ranging form Spanish influence, to Indian influence, to Mediterranean influence. The service was on point as well. We were directed to the main seating area by the host and the waitress took time to point out some of her favorites on the menu. She didn't seem to be very knowledgable on what each pasty included and the sauces were switched on my pastries, but all was forgiven after the first bite. There is a large private parking lot for the restaurant with free parking available. I'll be back next time I'm in town.",
